4. English Summary

  1. The Russian ruble is expected to strengthen due to recent capital control measures imposed by the Russian government on exporters. These measures require exporters to deposit a significant portion of their foreign currency earnings in Russian banks and sell most of their earnings on the domestic market. This will increase the amount of foreign currency in the Russian market, strengthening the ruble. As a result, it is anticipated that the ruble will strengthen to 88-92 rubles per dollar in the next 2-3 months, followed by a potential depreciation. This could lead to an outflow of capital from Russia, benefiting Armenias economy and banking system.

  2. In 2022, Armenia experienced a substantial increase in international money transfers, particularly from Russia, resulting in an influx of dollars into the countrys banking system. The significant inflow of foreign currency was coupled with a rise in outflows. This dynamic has been instrumental in influencing the exchange rate of the Armenian dram against the US dollar.

  3. A portion of the report discusses the rising gasoline prices in Armenia, which have increased significantly over the past year. Factors contributing to this increase include the devaluation of the dram, global oil market dynamics, OPEC+ oil production restrictions, and Russias export embargo on gasoline, leading to internal shortages in Armenia. The rising gasoline prices are seen as a political issue with global and domestic implications.
